	<clause id="_vapour_pressure_relations" obligation="normative"><title>VAPOUR-PRESSURE RELATIONS</title><clause id="_helium_vapour_pressure_relations" obligation="normative"><title>Helium vapour-pressure relations</title><p id="_eb3d7558-da89-4f74-ae00-6d288f6537c1">The vapour-pressure relations for helium are of the form</p>
	<formula id="eq1">
	<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub><mo>/</mo><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>A</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>A</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mi>ln</mi><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>/</mo><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>a</mi></mrow></mstyle></mrow></mfenced><mo>−</mo><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle><mo>/</mo><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>C</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msup><mi>.</mi></math></stem>
	</formula>
	<p id="_f5c12850-6e4f-42a4-870d-bc0b2f5346e7">Values of the constants <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>A</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem>, <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>A</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>, <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>C</mi></mstyle></math></stem> are given in Table 3 of the Text of the ITS-90 for the three ranges <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>0.65</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem> to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>3.2</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem> for <sup>3</sup>He; <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>1.25</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem> to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>2.1768</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem> for <sup>4</sup>He (<sup>4</sup>He II); and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>2.1768</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem> to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>5.0</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem> also for <sup>4</sup>He (<sup>4</sup>He I)<fn reference="1"><p id="_6ff352e2-1607-4fdb-8d96-cfbb6b69d042">In the phase diagram of <sup>4</sup>He, the liquid phases above and below the lambda line are distinguished by referring them as <sup>4</sup>He I and <sup>4</sup>He II, respectively. The properties of superfluid <sup>4</sup>He II are very different from those of <sup>4</sup>He I.</p></fn>. The <sup>4</sup>He equations coincide at the lambda point (<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>2.1768</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem>, <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>5041.8</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>a</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></stem>) with a first derivative <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mtext>d</mtext><mi>ln</mi><mi>p</mi><mo>/</mo><mtext>d</mtext><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>2.461</mn><mtext> </mtext><msup><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msup></math></stem>. In deriving these equations, no constraints were placed at the second derivative, which is discontinuous at this point.</p>
